<item>
 <title>Teacher Librarians: Using Emerging Technologies to Build a Personal Learning Network</title>
 <link>https://ejournalism.lskysd.ca/node/39</link>
 <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;Donna DesRoches, a former teacher-librarian, is the Learning Resources Consultant with the Living Sky School Division.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Her presentation was about the importance of teacher librarians using new technologies to stay connected and to learn from what their peers have written. She began her presentation by explaining how she discovered the use of social networking sites to learn. Her “ahha” moment occurred in 1993 at a Dean Shareski presentation.
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;Donna has become so involved in using and promoting technology because she recognizes the student benefits and she wants to ensure that the new technologies don’t pass her by. She believes that teachers should be aware of the ways students are interacting with each other so they can help the students to optimize the experience. She says that there are different ways students use the internet. One way, which she calls “messing around”, is just trying out different things to see how they work and what they do. Another way, which she calls “geeking out” &lt;span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;is people who connect with others that are educated about the technologies that they want to learn about.
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;Donna loves her personal learning networks. She says that they provide her with support, new ideas, and keep her “in the loop” about new ideas, technologies, and books.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;It is a way to brainstorm and share ideas to develop a global spectrum of perspective. She says to start small and don’t try to get to everything all at once.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Fifteen minutes a day is a great way to start.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Be strategic about where you want to go and what you want to read.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Don’t overwhelm yourself.
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;    &lt;/span&gt;Donna talked about the key strategies to get involved in personal networking.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Start by reading blogs and collecting resources.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Remember to keep the same user names and passwords.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;(avoids a lot of confusion)&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Also, use your real name.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;With your students, encourage them to use their real names as they are creating a virtual footprint where future employers can look them up.
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;After you have done a lot of reading on a subject, you are
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;ready to share.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Start by commenting on what you’re reading. Start a simple blog of your own… Just put down your ideas.
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;Now you’re ready to connect.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Twhirl pops up when you have something new on Twitter etc. Start to network on Yammer (Only people in your school division can be on it). Tag Key words to make them easy to find later… Delicious, Flickr, YouTube.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;comic sans ms,sand&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ffffff&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;        &lt;/span&gt;For more of Donna’s ideas, click on the link provided.
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
